 he came to new york at the age of  through the influence of a cousin he got a job selling  dresses on seventh avenue but was happier when he was put in charge of the companys piece‐goods department advertisement continue reading the main story he entered the beauty business while still in his early s selling the nail polish that was then available—a thin translucent coating in a few basic colos he left his employer the elka company in  when he was refused the job of national distributor continue reading the main story advertisement continue reading the main story revlon was born the same year when mr revson and his older brother joseph met charles lachman the l in revlon a chemist who had experimented over a bunsen burner and produced a formula for a creamy opaque nonstreak nail polish the three pooled their resources a matter of  and went into business in a room on manhattans west sideconcentrated on salonsthe company grew even during the depression because of mr revsons decision to concentrate his sales efforts on beauty salons which were then in the midst of the permanentwave boom even after revlon began to sell through department and drug stores in  the salon business remained its major preoccupation for some years by  revlon had a near monopoly in the estimated total of  beauty salons throughout the country selling in bulk to the professional operators and to the women who bought their cosmetics at the salons the dominance built up during that period exists to this daymr revson was generally recognized as the moving force of the company and the visionary both in new‐product development in his younger days he often walked‐around with nails dabbed with polish and hands striped with lipstick and in the advertising that pushed revlon to national prominencerevlon introduced the concept of “matching lips and fingertips” in —earlier colors of lipstick and nail polish had not been thus coordinated and there were only a few shades generally light medium and dark in each this was followed by magazine advertising that promoted revlons varied glamorous colors and romantic names it was consistently brilliant and considered the best in the industry in  the “fire and ice” advertisement was introduced it is still considered one of the classics of the beauty businessdespite the extraordinary magazine impact most of it sparked by mr revsons demand for nothing less than perfection revlons television efforts were until  mediocre in that year revlon began sponsorship of “the  question” with a clause unusual at the time that gave it the right to abandon the program after  weeks should it prove a dud after its first showing mr revson was unconvinced about its drawing power“its a turkey” he told colleagues who gathered after the showswamped with demandnevertheless from the day the program went on the air the company was swamped with dealer demand sales rose  per cent earnings went up almost  per cent and even the resultant quiz‐show scandals could not diminish the impact revlon shares which had just been offered to the public at  a share rose to  in three monthsin the ensuing years new products and use of advertising continued their parallel courses in pushing revlon to the top of the industry cosmetics skin care products shampoos and hair sprays fragrances and mens products in a wide range prices spewed forth from the fertile minds of company and advertising executives from revlons product‐development laboratory and from acquisitions the trade names marketed by revlon included ultima ii princess marcella borghese moon drops intimate fianima replique miss balmain etherea bill blass braggi and royal pub the advertising budget ‐million in  grew to ‐million by by the early nineteen‐sixties joseph revson and mr lachman had resigned from the company a younger brother martin who entered the business in  resigned in  and sued his brother on charges of fraud misrepresentation and breach of agreement in a stock deal the suit was settled out of court but the brothers remained estranged until after josephs death in  martin revson is now head of dell laboratories manufacturer of inexpensive cosmetics advertisement continue reading the main story decision to diversifyone of charles revsons most orilliant business moves was his decision in  to diversify his cosmetics empire by nibbling off a tiny piece of the hugely profitable pharmaceutical industry against the advice of most of his associates he paid ‐million for the united states vitamin and pharmaceutical corporation a sleepy drug company with modest sales of ‐million a yearas he had with revlon mr revson soon began adding products to the usv line cross‐licensing agreements with foreign companies brought with them the right to market new drugs in this country and elsewhere and a  exchange lagreement with the ciba‐geigy corporbtion gave usv certain marketing rights patents and trademarks for four widely used drugs and marketing rights to  additional drugs revlon expanded into  new and different therapeutic categories and in return ciba‐geigy received ‐million in cash and the rights to market an oral diabetic drugless than a decade after he had entered the pharmaceutical industry  per cent of the sales of revlon inc and  per cent of its profits derived from sales of health products in the united states and  other countriesby  the revlon product range had grown to more than  individual items sold in  countries the companys sales totaled ‐million and net earnings were ‐millionmr revsons business judgment was not however infallible involvements with businesses as diverse as plastic flowers and loungewear made in hong kong and sportswear made in the united states were terminated in a comparatively short time the companys fouryear ownership of evan‐picone the sportswear house resulted in a loss of ‐million when it was sold in interest in clothesalthough his professional ventures into the fashion industry were peripheral and shortlived mr revsons personal interest in the clothes worn by his third wife the former lyn fisher sheresky their ‐year marriage ended in divorce in  resulted in one of his most astute business tie‐upsat one time the late designer norman norell would send his collection to the revlon office where mr revson selected styles for his wife liter mr revson began to accompany his wife to fashionable showroom openingshe thought so highly of the designers talents that he made a business arrangement with him under which the norell name went on revlons most prestigious perfume it was fortuitous timing the venture came just as a fragrance boom was beginning and the new scent norell became what many considered the first great american perfume mr revson aware of the fragrance trend soon followed norell with charlie a less expensive scent aimed at a younger market advertisement continue reading the main story although revlon was built on its sales to women mr revson employed few of them in key positions“i dont think he trusted womens thinking to any degree” commented one who knew him well and who remembered his comment that “a man gets his strength from a woman and then he goes on from there”opposite ends of roomhowever because of the nature of the cosmetics business women were the objects of his principal business vendettas he was loath to mention the name of his competitors and it was known as the height of folly to invite the revlon founder and estee lauder a chief rival in the field to the same party when the two did find themselves in the same room they pretended they werent and proceeded with entourages to opposite endsmr revson had the last word in earlier business feuds although he did not retaliate publicly while they were going on the late elizabeth arden called him “that man” and he so named one of his mens fragrances the late helena rubinstein referred to him as “the nail man” after her death he bought her park avenue triplex he also made certain that he surmounted other cosmetics companies in the general motors building home of revlons corporate headquarters estée lauders offices are on the th floor and helena rubinsteins until a recent move were the d revlon is at the topthe prestige built up by estée lauder and the fact that mr revson and mrs lauder both moved with international society perhaps accounted for mr revsons increasing preoccupation with building up his own name in his later years“charles revson” began to be used in advertising copy and news releases went out on paper emblazoned with inch‐high gold letters outlining the name and although he was known as charles to his friends he was not averse to the marketing of the name charliekept eye on detailsdespite his interest in the social whirl and the amount of time he spent aboard the ultima h the ‐foot ‐ton yacht he bought from daniel k ludwig multimillionaire shipbuilder mr revson never lost contact with his office he was aware of the smallest details within the organization and was never hesitant in voicing opinion or criticism“he chewed up executives the way some people chew vitamins” said one chewed‐up executive who noted that even the hefty financial rewards offered by the company were nut sufficient to prevent a considerable turnover in upper‐echelon personnel and in advertising agencies at one time the corporate headquarters was dubbed “one big revolving door”at meetings mr revson had a reputation for lowering the heavy lids over his sharp blue eyes and assuming a sleepy look the knowledgeable were aware that the pose did not affect his vision he pounced when it was least expected and conferences would go on long after everyone else was weary advertisement continue reading the main story his employes were rarely told that they did a good job an omission many found frustrating others were irked at the atmosphere engendered by his personal likes and dislikes office romances were frowned on women in pants were merely tolerated and beards and brown shoes on male employes were restricted “not by dictum but by tone”enjoyed his successmr revson fully enjoyed the accouterments of success—the yacht the triplex a country estate in westchester a chauffeur‐driven rolls‐royce and the tailors and barbers who came to him he enjoyed too helping friends in distressas a man who never went to college he took a particular satisfaction in seeing his name on medical centers and fellowships the charles revson diagnostic center at the albert einstein college of medicine the charles revson institute of ophthalmology at new york medical center graduate fellowships at brandeis university revson plaza at columbia university he also contributed important sums of money to the salk institute and various charitiesalthough there had been some speculation about mr revsons unwillingness to groom a successor the guessing was brought to an end in  shortly before he underwent surgery mr revson named michel g bergerac former president of itt europe inc as president of revlonbesides his brother martin mr revson is survived by two sons john who is vice president of the companys etherea fine fragrance division and charles jr who is director of marketing fragrances of the borghese division an adopted daughter penelope revson and one grandchild the sons are the children of his second marriage to joanna katrinka de knecht who is now mrs ben johnson of palm beach fla mr revsons first marriage to ida tompkins also ended in divorcea funeral service will he held tomorrow at  pm in temple emanu‐el fifth avenue and th street continue reading the main story whats next loading go to home page » site index the new york times charles revson trademark of charles revson inc serial number   trademarkia trademarks apply online attorneys services us trademark registration service international trademark registration service trademark office action response trademark statement of use trademark renewal trademark assignment trademark watch trademark cease  desist trademark comprehensive search copyright registration patent services